<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-11-30T18:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-11-30T18:00:00-05:00" n="832" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d832">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 600.119/1686</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                the Ambassador in Spain</hi> (<persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_WJE1" type="to"><hi rend="italic">Willard</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-11-30T18:00:00-05:00">
                                    <hi rend="italic">November 30, 1918, 6 p.m.</hi>
                                </date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>1849. For <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_CTL1">Chadbourne</persName> [from War Trade Board]:</p>
                        <p>No. 383. Embassy’s 2113, November 20, 10 a.m., your 392. Bunker
                            restrictions at Cuban ports are under the complete jurisdiction of Cuban
                            authorities as conveyed in proclamation by President of Cuba under date
                            June 24 [<hi rend="italic">26?</hi>], 1918. War Trade Board
                            representative at Habana has only such authority as is delegated by
                            Cuban authorities. Cuban Government has in fact been disposed to accept
                            our suggestions relative to applying bunker control, and the fact that
                            Cuba’s imports of coal are from the United States gives us considerable
                            influence in determining the utilization thereof in Cuba.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_LR1">
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Lansing</hi>
                                </persName>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                </body></text></TEI>